# VisordeRiesgoSismico — MERISUR

Seismic Risk Viewer developed as a Final Degree Project (TFG) at the Universidad Politécnica de Madrid, TERRA Research Group.

The application calculates and visualises the expected seismic damage to buildings in Lorca and Puerto Lumbreras (Murcia, Spain) for user-defined earthquake scenarios, including debris estimation, debris barriers and census-section-level analysis.

> **Acknowledgement:** The original seismic calculation engine (distance metrics, ground motion model, vulnerability and debris functions) was developed by **Pouye Yazdi** at the Universidad Politécnica de Madrid (2017). This project extends and integrates that work.

---

## Tech Stack

- **Backend:** Node.js + Express
- **Frontend:** HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Leaflet.js
- **Seismic calculation:** Python 3.10 (geopandas, shapely, pygmm, scipy, pyproj, geopy)
- **Database:** MongoDB Atlas (shared cloud database)
- **Ground motion model:** Akkar-Sandikkaya-Bommer 2014

---

## Architecture

The application runs **locally** on each machine but shares a **common cloud database** (MongoDB Atlas). This means:

- Each user clones the repository and runs the server on their own machine
- All users read and write to the same Atlas database (shared users, sessions, results)
- The seismic calculation engine runs locally using Python and the local GIS input files
- Email verification links use `APP_URL`, which must be set to the machine's local address

---

## Prerequisites

- Node.js v18 or higher
- Python 3.10
- Git + Git LFS
- Access credentials to the shared MongoDB Atlas cluster (contact the project author)

---

## Installation

### 1. Clone the repository

Make sure Git LFS is installed first:

```bash
git lfs install
```

Then clone:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/alejagranizo/VisordeRiesgoSismico.git
cd VisordeRiesgoSismico
```

Git LFS will automatically download the large GIS input files (shapefiles, etc.) during clone.

### 2. Install Node.js dependencies

```bash
npm install
```

### 3. Create a Python virtual environment and install dependencies

```bash
python -m venv pythonCode/env
pythonCode\env\Scripts\activate      # Windows
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 4. Set up environment variables

Create a `.env` file in the project root based on `.env.example`:

```
PORT=3000

# Shared cloud database — use the Atlas URI provided by the project author
MONGO_URI=mongodb+srv://user:password@cluster.mongodb.net/merisurDB

SESSION_SECRET=your_secret_here

# Absolute paths — adjust to your machine
MAIN_PATH=C:/YourPath/pythonCode/MAIN.py
MAIN_Secc_PATH=C:/YourPath/pythonCode/MAIN0.py
FAULT_JSON=C:/YourPath/pythonCode/inputs/fault_params.json
PYTHON_CODE_PATH=C:/YourPath/pythonCode
PYTHON_EXE=C:/YourPath/pythonCode/env/Scripts/python.exe

# Email configuration
MAIL_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
MAIL_PORT=587
MAIL_USER=your_email@gmail.com
MAIL_PASS=your_gmail_app_password
TECH_EMAIL=admin_email@domain.com

# Your machine's local address — used in email verification links
# Use http://localhost:3000 if you are the only user
# Use http://192.168.X.X:3000 (your local IP) if others need to open links from a different device
APP_URL=http://localhost:3000
```

> **MAIL_PASS** is not your regular Gmail password. Generate an App Password at **Google Account → Security → 2-Step Verification → App Passwords**.

> **APP_URL** is used to build the links inside verification emails. If the email is opened on a different device, `localhost` will not resolve — set this to your local network IP (`ipconfig` on Windows) so links work from any device on the same network.

> **MONGO_URI** must point to the shared Atlas cluster to collaborate. Using `mongodb://localhost:27017/merisurDB` creates a fully isolated local database that no one else can see.

### 5. Generate debris buffers (first time only)

Buffer GeoJSON files are not stored in the repository and must be generated before running any seismic scenario:

```bash
cd pythonCode

# Generate buffers for both municipalities (recommended)
python GENERATE_BUFFERS.py

# Generate only for Lorca
python GENERATE_BUFFERS.py LORCA

# Generate only for Puerto Lumbreras
python GENERATE_BUFFERS.py PL
```

This produces the following files:
- `inputs/Lorca/allBuffers_Lorca1-4.geojson`
- `inputs/Lorca/allBuildings_Lorca.txt` (updated with facade lengths)
- `inputs/PuertoLumbreras/allBuffers_PL1-4.geojson`
- `inputs/PuertoLumbreras/allBuildings_PL.txt` (updated with facade lengths)

> This step can take several minutes. It only needs to be run once, or again if the building shapefiles change.

### 6. Start the server

```bash
npm start
```

The application will be available at `http://localhost:3000`.

---

## Project Structure

```
merisurNode/
├── app.js                  # Main Node.js server
├── routes/                 # Express routes (auth, data)
├── public/                 # Frontend (HTML, CSS, JS, GIS data)
│   └── newData/            # Census-section geometries as JS files
├── pythonCode/             # Python seismic calculation modules
│   ├── MAIN.py             # Per-building calculation (manual scenario)
│   ├── MAIN0.py            # Orchestrator (RISK_ + BUFF_)
│   ├── RISK_.py            # Damage calculation by census section
│   ├── BUFF_.py            # Geometry + results merger
│   ├── GENERATE_BUFFERS.py # Debris buffer generation (LORCA / PL / both)
│   ├── inputs/             # Input data (shapefiles, txt) — tracked via Git LFS
│   └── output/             # Generated results (git-ignored)
├── requirements.txt        # Python dependencies
├── package.json            # Node.js dependencies
├── .env.example            # Environment variable template
└── README.md               # This file
```

---

## Usage

1. Open `http://localhost:3000` and log in.
2. Select a seismic fault and configure the scenario (magnitude, focal mechanism, probability level).
3. Click **Calculate** — the system runs the Python scripts in the background.
4. The map updates with the results: per-building damage, debris volumes, and census-section analysis.

---

## Required Input Data

The following files must be present in `pythonCode/inputs/` and are included in the repository via Git LFS:

- `Lorca/allBuildings_cusec.txt` — raw building inventory for Lorca
- `Lorca/shapefiles/EdificiosLorca2026.shp` — building footprints
- `Lorca/shapefiles/LorcaSoil_WGS.*` — Vs30 soil map
- `PuertoLumbreras/allBuildings_cusec_PL.txt` — raw building inventory for Puerto Lumbreras
- `PuertoLumbreras/shapefiles/EdificiosPuertoLumbreras.shp` — building footprints
- `params.xlsx` — vulnerability and debris parameter tables

---

## Collaborating

This project uses a shared MongoDB Atlas database. To collaborate:

1. Request the Atlas `MONGO_URI` from the project author
2. Clone the repository and follow the installation steps above
3. Set `MONGO_URI` in your `.env` to the shared Atlas URI
4. Any users registered or data generated will be visible to all collaborators

To pull the latest code changes:

```bash
git pull
```

